First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in both. 

A △ B = {x: x ∈ A or x ∈ B, but not both}

A △ B = {5, 7, 11, 13, 17}

Now, let's find the intersection of the sets A and B. The intersection of two sets is the set of elements which are in both sets.

A ∩ B = {x: x ∈ A and x ∈ B}

A ∩ B = {2, 3}

Now, let's compare the result of (A △ B) ∩ B with the result of (B △ A) ∩ A.

(A △ B) ∩ B = {5, 7, 11, 13, 17} ∩ {2, 3, 13, 17} = {13, 17}

(B △ A) ∩ A = {5, 7, 11, 13, 17} ∩ {2, 3, 5, 7, 11} = {5, 7, 11}

As we can see, (A △ B) ∩ B ≠ (B △ A) ∩ A, which shows that the symmetric difference is not commutative with respect to intersection.
